<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,1650,2036]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,1890,1916]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Specimens with tricolor dorsal pattern cannot be mistaken with any other known 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Exochomoscirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Exochomoscirtes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Rare forms with black &amp; red pattern can be distinguished from related species by the peculiar dorsal metatibial spur in the male which is somewhat similar to the one in 
<taxonomicName authority="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi, 2010" authorityName="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi" authorityYear="2010" box="[961,1130,1971,1996]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Exochomoscirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dilaticornis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[961,1130,1971,1996]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">E. dilaticornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1139,1230,1970,1996]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi, 2010" authorityName="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi" authorityYear="2010" box="[1290,1436,1971,1996]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Exochomoscirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="takizawai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1290,1436,1971,1996]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">E. takizawai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,241,2010,2036]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="29" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,151,858]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,350,151,177]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[362,474,152,178]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Holotype</typeStatus>
, male. Body hemispherical, TL/EW 1.2, convex, covered with yellow suberect setae. Head black with brownish anterior margin of clypeus, pronotum black, elytra with color pattern. Posterior portion of elytra, humeri, and oval macula in adsutural portion of anterior half of elytra black. Remaining parts of elytra yellow and orange. Legs light brown. Mouthparts brownish, antennomeres 1–3 yellowish, 4–11 black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,151,858]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Head with distinct punctation, punctures separated by ca. 1.0 diameter. Eyes big, protuberant; head 1.7 X wider than interocular space. Antennae filiform, reaching basal 1/3 of elytra. Antennomere 1 cylindrical, curved, antennomere 2 short, globular, antennomere 3 distinctly longer than antennomere 2, narrow, antennomere 4–10 1.5 X longer than antennomere 3, apical antennomere ca. 1.5 X longer than preapical one. Palpomeres of maxillary palpi moderately wide.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,151,858]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Pronotum small, slightly convex, covered with distinct punctation, punctures separated by 1.0–2.0 diameters, anterolateral corners almost rectangular, somewhat obtuse, projecting anteriorly; lateral margins straight; posterolateral corners acute; base of pronotum subtrapezoidal, with incomplete margination along basal margin; PW/PL 2.8. Scutellum relatively big, punctured as on pronotum, equilaterally triangular. Angle between pronotum and elytra not marked in dorsal outline.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,151,858]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Elytra oval, with distinctly explanate lateral margins, widest in the middle, punctation stronger than on pronotum, punctures separated by 1.0–2.0 diameters; humeri well marked; EL/EW 1.1; EL/PL 5.2; EW/PW 1.6.</paragraph>
<caption pageId="27" pageNumber="28" startId="27.[151,255,1587,1611]" targetBox="[183,1388,936,1544]" targetPageId="27">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,1587,1645]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,295,1587,1611]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">FIGURE 20.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi, 2010" authorityName="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi" authorityYear="2010" box="[302,599,1588,1611]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Exochomoscirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="picturatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[302,599,1588,1611]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Exochomoscirtes picturatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[606,691,1588,1611]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, male. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[768,796,1587,1611]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">A)</emphasis>
sternite 9; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[916,943,1587,1611]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">B)</emphasis>
tergite 8; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1053,1081,1587,1611]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">C)</emphasis>
tergite 9; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1190,1219,1587,1611]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">D)</emphasis>
aedeagus. Scale bar = 0.5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption box="[151,1167,2004,2028]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" startId="27.[151,255,2004,2028]" targetBox="[151,1436,1700,1980]" targetPageId="27">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1167,2004,2028]" box="[151,1167,2004,2028]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,294,2004,2028]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">FIGURE 21.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi, 2010" authorityName="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi" authorityYear="2010" box="[301,598,2004,2027]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Exochomoscirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="picturatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[301,598,2004,2027]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Exochomoscirtes picturatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[604,689,2004,2027]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, female 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[779,847,2004,2028]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">A)–B)</emphasis>
prehensor and bursal sclerite.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,152,1338]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Legs moderately long. Hind tibial spurs well developed, dorsal one elongate, apex modified – widened and tridentate, 0.9 X as long as tarsomere 1 and slightly longer than ventral spur. Ventral spur almost straight, somewhat shorter than tarsomere 1. Apex of dorsal spur widened, hooked, trifid apically.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,152,1338]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Ventrites 1 and 2 with sparse setation in mesal portion, ventrite 2 with basal row of big punctures. Apex of tergite 7 unmodified. Apex of ventrite 5 truncate.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,152,1338]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Sternite 9 (L 0.72, 
<geoCoordinate box="[425,515,352,378]" degrees="0.30" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" precision="555" value="-0.3">W 0.30</geoCoordinate>
) subtriangular, apodemes fused basally, apex deeply emarginated, with a few apical setae. Tergite 8 (L 1.38, 
<geoCoordinate box="[533,625,392,418]" degrees="0.50" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" precision="555" value="-0.5">W 0.50</geoCoordinate>
) moderately sclerotized, apical portion small, deeply and narrowly emarginated, with arcuate apex, bearing row of short setae on apical margin, with a pair of very long apodemes diverging basally; tergite 9 (L 0.84, 
<geoCoordinate box="[659,748,472,498]" degrees="0.56" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" precision="555" value="-0.56">W 0.56</geoCoordinate>
) moderately sclerotized, apical portion small, with minute setae at apex, with a pair of long apodemes diverging basally. Tegmen (L 0.78, 
<geoCoordinate box="[1130,1221,512,538]" degrees="0.61" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" precision="555" value="-0.61">W 0.61</geoCoordinate>
) well sclerotized, parameres straight, widening apically, inwardly pointed at apices, mesal process very narrow and short, much shorter than parameres. Penis (L 0.39, 
<geoCoordinate box="[607,696,592,618]" degrees="0.09" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" precision="555" value="-0.09">W 0.09</geoCoordinate>
) small, moderately sclerotized, pala very narrow and elongate, apical process evenly shorter than pala.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,152,1338]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,296,671,697]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Female.</emphasis>
Metatibial spurs unmodified, dorsal spur almost straight, slightly shorter than tarsomere 1, ventral spur half as long as dorsal one. Dorsal pattern lighter (see: variability). Prehensor tubular, narrow and moderately long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,152,1338]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,338,791,817]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Variability.</emphasis>
TL/EW in males 1.2, TL/EW in females 1.2–1.3 (1.3). Dorsal pattern extremely variable. Males with black pronotum and usually tricolor elytral pattern: humeral portion, postscutellar macula and posterior portion of elytra black, stripes connecting black maculae orange, remaining area yellow. One specimen is dark with bicolor elytra, each elytron black with two orange maculae: an oval basal one and a transversely oval one in the middle of the elytra. Females with pronotum yellow to brown, elytra orange with black pattern consisting of humeral maculae, postscutellar macula and transverse stripe in posterior portion of elytra. One female specimen (coll. NHM) is darker, anterior 2/3 of elytra are brownish-black with oval orange macula in basal portion of elytra and transversely oval macula in the middle length of elytra, posterior 1/3 of elytra orange. Several color variations are shown on 
<figureCitation box="[694,832,1112,1138]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="17.[151,255,1886,1910]" captionTargetBox="[164,1425,210,1820]" captionTargetId="figure-69@17.[152,1434,197,1860]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 11. Habitus illustrations of Exochomoscirtes. A) E. bimaculatus Pic; B) E. basipunctatus sp. nov.; C) E. binotatus Pic; D) E. rufomaculatus Pic; E) E. ephippiatus (Champion); F)–I) E. picturatus sp. nov., color forms; J)–L) E. takizawai sp. nov., color forms; M) E. tetrastigma (Champion). Scale bar = 2.0 mm." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Figs. 11F–I</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,152,1338]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,389,1151,1177]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Measurements.</emphasis>
Males (n = 4): TL 3.78–4.50 (4.25), PL 0.65–0.80 (0.73), PW 1.85–2.35 (2.13), EL 3.40– 4.15 (3.83), EW 3.13–3.70 (3.50). Females (n = 4): TL 4.00–4.27 (4.17), PL 0.70–0.75 (0.74), PW 1.95–2.13 (2.08), EL 3.68–3.92 (3.81), EW 3.20–3.40 (3.28).
</paragraph>
